{"id":"1812.11388","submitter":"Michael Ruddy","authors":"Irina A. Kogan, Michael Ruddy, Cynthia Vinzant","title":"Differential signatures of algebraic curves","comments":"35 pages, 2 figures; v2: The result on the upper bound for the\n  degrees of signature polynomials is generalized to arbitrary subgroups of the\n  projective group","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.DG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we adapt the differential signature construction to the\nequivalence problem for complex plane algebraic curves under the actions of the\nprojective group and its subgroups. Given an action of a group $G$, a signature\nmap assigns to a plane algebraic curve another plane algebraic curve (a\nsignature curve) in such a way that two generic curves have the same signatures\nif and only if they are $G$-equivalent. We prove that for any $G$-action, there\nexists a pair of rational differential invariants, called classifying\ninvariants, that can be used to construct signatures. We derive a formula for\nthe degree of a signature curve in terms of the degree of the original curve,\nthe size of its symmetry group and some quantities depending on a choice of\nclassifying invariants. For the full projective group, as well as for its\naffine, special affine and special Euclidean subgroups, we give explicit sets\nof rational classifying invariants and derive a formula for the degree of the\nsignature curve of a generic curve as a quadratic function of the degree of the\noriginal curve. We show that this generic degree is the sharp upper bound.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 29 Dec 2018 15:54:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 10 Jun 2019 14:30:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-06-11"}
